ality of software, to evaluate said question:

So what about companies like WeWork and Peloton that interact with the real=
 world? Note the centrality of software in all of these characteristics:

* Software creates ecosystems.
* Software has zero marginal costs.
* Software improves over time.
* Software offers infinite leverage.
* Software enables zero transaction costs.

The question of whether companies are tech companies, then, depends on how =
much of their business is governed by software=E2=80=99s unique characteris=
tics, and how much is limited by real world factors.

It is interesting to apply these criteria to Instacart=E2=80=99s core groce=
ry delivery business:

* Instacart has created a multi-sided market between grocery stores, shoppe=
rs, and customers.
* Instacart carries very high marginal costs on a de facto basis, both in t=
erms of actually needing to buy food and having to pay pickers.
* Instacart=E2=80=99s product improves over time as it increases its networ=
k and data about shoppers.
* Instacart=E2=80=99s addressable market is gated by the necessity of partn=
ering with grocery stores and hiring shoppers.
* Instacart has significant transaction costs, both in terms of higher pric=
es and delivery fees, and also in terms of the delay incurred in receiving =
your groceries.

The verdict is pretty clear: not a tech company! Sure, Instacart can =E2=80=
=94 and has =E2=80=94 gotten better at every aspect of its operations, mean=
ingfully increasing margin on every transaction and, at least according to =
the company=E2=80=99s attempt to back out COVID-driven growth, continuously=
 growing both its customer base and its average customer spend, but this op=
eration looks like another interface for the real world that, for all of it=
s tech magic, is ultimately gated by real world constraints.

The good thing for Instacart, though, is that they have another company wit=
h a very different business model. From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.c=
om/news/articles/2023-09-19/instacart-s-ipo-puts-spotlight-on-its-evolution=
-into-ad-seller ) :

When Instacart starts trading on the Nasdaq on Tuesday, investors won=E2=80=
=99t be betting on a grocery-delivery company. They=E2=80=99ll be betting o=
n a data and advertising business. The company, best known for its army of =
gig-economy workers filling grocery orders, has spent years building up its=
 ad division =E2=80=94 a higher-margin operation that capitalizes on a trov=
e of shopping data. That evolution helped add sizzle to the IPO, which pric=
ed at the top end of its marketed range Monday. Now Instacart will test pub=
lic investors=E2=80=99 appetite for its new model.

It=E2=80=99s difficult to imagine an app better positioned to sell advertis=
ing:

* Instacart is opened by shoppers with a high intent to purchase.
* Instacart=E2=80=99s primary interface for surfacing products is search, w=
hich gives it the strongest possible signal as far as user interest, with t=
he ability to put relevant ads on top of the results page.
* Instacart=E2=80=99s primary offering is commoditized goods that are prima=
rily differentiated by branding.

Small wonder that PepsiCo, Inc. is purchasing $175 million of stock in a pr=
ivate placement; the CPG company might as well partake in the upside of spe=
nding an increasing amount of money on Instacart ads!

This business, if it stood alone, would also score very high on the aforeme=
ntioned criteria:

* Instacart has created a multi-sided market between shoppers and advertise=
rs.
* Instacart advertising has zero marginal costs.
* Instacart=E2=80=99s advertising capabilities will improve over time as it=
